Write & Modify Script

Script files should be named in a file_name.extension format such as script.sh
To create a file, use the touch command :

Using “touch” command
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ touch script.sh

Alternative #1 :

Use cat command to create a file with a redirect (denoted with the > symbol) :

Using “cat” command
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ cat > script.sh
Enter the following while in the “cat” command
#!/bin/bash
echo 'Hello World'

press CTRL + D while under cat command to exit and return to the prompt.

Using “cat” command to see what’s in the script.sh file
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ cat script.sh

              
#!/bin/bash

              
echo 'Hello World'

          

        


        
Alternative #2 :


        
Use nanocommand to modify the script :

        

          

              

                  
                  
                  
              

              
Using “nano” command

              

          

          

              
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ nano script.sh

          

        


        

          

              

              
Enter the following while in the “nano” command

              

          

          

              
#!/bin/bash

              
echo 'Goodbye World'

          

        

        
press CTRL + O to Overwrite the script.

        
press CTRL + X to Exit and return to the prompt.


        

          

              

                  
                  
                  
              

              
Using “cat” command to see what’s in the script.sh file

              

          

          

              
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ cat script.sh

              

              
#!/bin/bash

              
echo 'Goodbye World'

          

        

      

    


    

      

          Command Parameters
      

      

        
Note : -switch, --option=value or -flag | --flag refers to parameters that modify the behavior of the command, often starting with a dash - or double-dash --

        
Key Differences :

        

          
Aspect-Switch--Options-f, --Flag

          
SyntaxSingle hyphen, short (-v)Double hyphen, descriptive (--verbose)Single or double hyphen (-d, --debug)

          
ArgumentsTypically no argumentsOften requires a valueNo arguments

        


        
ls command stands for Lists, to see the contents of a directory (the files and subdirectories)


        

          
SwitchExplanation

          
-lfor long list format (also contains the permission)

          
-a--all, to show all contents (includes hidden files)

          
-h--human-readable, print sizes (with -l switch)

        


        
Some commands let you supply multiple switch by listing them separately or joining them together

        

          

              

                  
                  
                  
              

              
Use “-switch” with “ls” command

              

          

          

            
Multiple separate switch

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ls -l -a -h

          

          

            
Single-lined multiple switch

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ls -lah

          

        


        

          

              

              
 “ls” command output

              

          

          

              
total 8K
drwx------ 14 0x3b 0x3b 4.0K Aug 16 13:22 .
drwxrwx--x  4 0x3b 0x3b 4.0K Jul 17 09:42 ..
-rw-------  1 0x3b 0x3b   31 Aug 16 11:16 script.sh

          

        

        
        

          
FileMeaning

          
Single dot .the current directory

          
Double dot ..the parent directory

        


      

    


    

      

          File Type & Permission
      

      

          
Use the ls command with the –l (long) switch to display the contents of a directory in long format—this list will contain the permissions

          

            

                

                
“ls -l” command output

                

            

            

                
1┎───2───┒ 3 ┎───4───┒   5  ┎────6────┒    7
drwxrw­xrw­x 5 root root 4020 Nov 1 12:07 h4ck1ng
drwxrw­xrw­x 2 root root 4020 Nov 1 12:07 isN3v3r
drwxr­wxrw­x 2 0x3b 0x3b 4020 Nov 1 12:07 Th4t
drwxr­wxrw­x 3 0x3b 0x3b 4020 Nov 1 12:07 E4Sy

            

        


        
Following are the possible file type options in the 1st character of the ls -l output.

        
1 The file type

        

          
FileType

          
-normal

          
ddirectory

          
ssocket

          
llink

        

        
2 The permissions on the file for users (owner), groups, and others, respectively

        
3 The number of links

        
4 The owner of the file

        
5 The size of the file in bytes

        
6 When the file was created or last modified

        
7 The name of the file


        
Every file and directory are allocated with a level of permission

        

          
LevelPermissionDescription

          
rreadgrants permission only to open and view a file

          
wwriteallows users to view and edit a file

          
xexecute allows users to run a file (but not view or edit it)

        


        
Check the permission with ls command followed by a specific filename → script.sh  :

        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “ls” command

            

          

          

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ls -l script.sh

            
-rw-------  1 0x3b 0x3b   31 Aug 16 11:11 script.sh

          

        


        
Grant executable permission with chmod command :

        

          

            

                
                
                
            

            
Using “chmod” command to give executable permission

            

          

          

            
Without declaring UGO syntax before the plus “+” sign will set it to the first syntax (User) by default

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ chmod +x script.sh
            

            
Check the permission again with “ls” command

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ls -l script.sh

            
-rwx------  1 0x3b 0x3b   31 Aug 16 11:13 script.sh

          

        


        
The mark * is known for following :

        

          
ContextMeaningExample

          

            File systems & command lines (Linux, Windows, macOS)
            * is called a wildcard — it means “match anything”
            *.txt → matches all files ending in .txt
          

          

            Programming (globbing libraries, bash)
            * is used in a glob pattern — a syntax for matching character(s) in filenames or strings
            folder/*/*.jpg → matches all .jpg files one level deeper inside folder/
          

        

        

        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “chmod” command with wildcard

            

          

          

            
Will grant permission to leading “script” named files

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ chmod +x script.*

            

            
Will grant permission to files with trailing “.sh” extension

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ chmod +x *.sh

            

            
Will grant permission to all files within the current directory

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ chmod +x *

            

          

        


        
Use a shortcut to refer to permissions by using a single number to represent one rwx set of permissions.

        

          
BinaryOctalrwx

          
0000---

          
0011--x

          
0102-w-

          
0113-wx

          
1004r--

          
1015r-x

          
1106rw-

          
1117rwx

       


       
chmod’s symbolic method is often referred to as the UGO syntax which stands u for User (owner), g for Group, and o for Others;

      
       
Lastly, a syntax for All which represents the entire UGO syntax.

       
        

            

                

                
UGO Syntax

                

            

            

                
PERMISSIONS     EXAMPLE
┎────A────┒
 U   G   O
rwx rwx rwx     chmod 777 filename
rwx rwx r-x     chmod 775 filename
rwx r-x r-x     chmod 755 filename
rw- rw- r--     chmod 664 filename
r-- r-- r--     chmod 444 filename

            

        


        
Use rwx permission to a specific UGO syntax :

        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “chmod” command with rwx permission

            

          

          

            
Will grant rwx permissions to UGO (User, Group, Others)

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ chmod u+rwx,g+r,o+r script.sh

            

            
Check the permission again with “ls” command

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ls -l script.sh

            
-rwxr--r--  1 0x3b 0x3b   31 Aug 16 11:17 script.sh

          

        


        
Use a syntax instead to apply permission for all of UGO syntax :

        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “chmod” command with “a” syntax

            

          

          

            
Will grant rwx permissions to ALL of UGO syntax

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ chmod a+x script.sh

            

            
Check the permission again with “ls” command

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ls -l script.sh

            
-rwxr-xr-x  1 0x3b 0x3b   31 Aug 16 11:21 script.sh

          

        


        
Use Octal permission (shortcut) :

        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “chmod” command octal permission

            

          

          

            
Will grant rwx permissions to UGO (User, Group, Others)

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ chmod 777 script.sh

            

            
Check the permission again with “ls” command

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ls -l script.sh

            
-rwxrwxrwx  1 0x3b 0x3b   31 Aug 16 11:27 script.sh

          

        

      

    


    

      

          Coding with Interpreter
      

      

        
Scripts all begin with the same line, a character sequence that starts with the hash # and exclamation mark ! called the shebang #!


        
We then follow the shebang with /bin/bash indicating that we want the operating system to use the BASH interpreter


        
Bourne-Again SHell (BASH) :

        

          

              

              
Using “bash” interpreter in the script

              

          

          

              
#!/bin/bash

          

        


        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “bash” command

            

          

          

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ bash script.sh

          

        


        
We can also run the script by using dot-slash notation ./ followed by the script’s name.


        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “dot-slash” notation command

            

          

          

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ./script.sh

          

        


        
The dot . represents the current directory, so we’re essentially telling bash to run script.sh from the current working directory.


        
Use -switch with BASH :


        

          
SwitchExplanation

          
-xdisplays commands and their results. Useful for debugging.

          
-vVerbose, displays everything even comments and spaces.

          
-eError Exit, causing the script to immediately exit on the first error.

          
-fchecks if the file exists and is a regular file.

          
-rcreates a restricted bash shell,
which restricts certain potentially dangerous commands.

          
-nwill read the commands but won’t execute them,
any syntax errors will be shown onscreen.

        


        

          

              

              
Using “-switch” interpreter in the script

              

          

          

              
#!/bin/bash -x -v -e

          

        


        
Specifying an argument within the shebang line requires modifying the script, but you can also pass arguments to the bash interpreter.

        

          

              

                  
                  
                  
              

              
Use “-switch” with “bash” command

              

          

          

            
Multiple separate switch

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ bash -x -v -e script.sh
            

            
Single-lined multiple switch

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ bash -xve script.sh

          

        


        
Whether you pass arguments to the bash interpreter on the command line or on the shebang line won’t make a difference.


        
SHELL (SH) :

        

          

              

              
Using “shell” interpreter in the script

              

          

          

              
#!/bin/sh

          

        


        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “sh” command

            

          

          

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ sh script.sh

          

        


        
PYTHON (PY) :

        

          

              

              
Using “python” interpreter in the script

              

          

          

              
#!/usr/bin/python

          

        


        
Alternative :

        

          

              

              
Using alternative “python” interpreter in the script

              

          

          

              
#!/usr/bin/env python

          

        


        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “python” command

            

          

          

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ python script.py

          

        


        
JAVA :

        

          

              

              
Using “java” programming language

              

          

          

            
Can run script without #!shebang
            

            
public class script {
  public static void main (String args[]) {
  }
}

          

        


        

          

              

                  
                  
                  
              

              
Use “java” and “javac” commands

              

          

          

            
Creates a .class file of script.java

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ javac script.java
            

            
Runs the generated script.class

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ java script

          

        

      

    


    

      

          Script Argument
      

      

        
Pass an Argument to a script from a Command Line


        
Note : Argument refers to any input passed to a command
Use “World” as command line argument


        
Bourne-Again SHell (BASH) :

        

          

              

              
Using “bash” interpreter in the script

              

          

          

              
#!/bin/bash

              
echo "Hello $1"

          

        


        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “dot-slash” notation command

            

          

          

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ ./script.sh World

            
OUTPUT: Hello World

          

        


        
PYTHON (PY) :

        

          

              

              
Using “python” interpreter in the script

              

          

          

              
#!/usr/bin/python

              
print("Hello", __import__('sys').argv[1])

          

        

        
        
Alternative :


        

          

              

              
Using alternative “python” script

              

          

          

              
import sys

              
print("Hello %s" % sys.argv[1])

          

        


        

          

            

              
              
              
            

            
Using “python” command

            

          

          

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ python script.py World

            
OUTPUT: Hello World

          

        


        
JAVA :

        

          

              

              
Using “java” programming language

              

          

          

            
Can run script without #!shebang
            

            
public class script {
  public static void main(String args[]) {
    System.out.print("Hello " + args[0]);
  }
}

          

        


        

          

              

                  
                  
                  
              

              
Use “java” and “javac” commands

              

          

          

            
Creates a .class file of script.java

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ javac script.java
            

            
Runs the generated script.class

            
h4x0r@0x3b:~$ java script World
            

            
OUTPUT: Hello World
